Probate questions regarding omitted spouse
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> jrenf...@gmail.com </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-01-12T07:31:00 </POSTDATE>
My mom is in the middle of an ugly probate case and I was wondering if
anyone out there has knowledge of this.  First off, I should state that
this takes place in California.

Anyways, about a year ago, my mom's husband passed away after they had
been married for only a year.  He had not updated his trust, so the
property was passed down to his children.  Yet by the omitted spouse
clause, I believe that my mom was entitled to 1/3 or half the estate.
Now right after he had passed away, his children basically kicked my
mom out of the house and wouldn't give her any of the possessions that
they had bought together.

Now they are claiming that my mom and her husband had always agreed
that they would keep things separate and that if he were to die then
his kids would get the house.  This was never written down but they
have witnesses to claim to have heard them say this (including police
officers).  My mom claims that she agreed that she was going to let the
children have the house, but not the entire estate (which is worth a
lot more).  The children are saying in their proposal that they will
give my mom half of the possessions bought while they were married and
90% of the debt that was incrued (a lot of it is from traveling).  I'm
not sure how they can justify that 90% though.  They are claiming that
it's because my mom made him travel a lot for vacations, but the way I
see it is that it's his money and his decision.

So do his children have a leg to stand on?  Nothing was written down
about not giving my mom any of the estate, so isn't some of that
automatically given to her under the omitted spouse clause?

Thanks for any help!
-Josiah
