That's right.  See California Probate Code §21610.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Now they are claiming that my mom and her husband had always
&gt; agreed that they would keep things separate and that if he were to
&gt; die then his kids would get the house.  This was never written
&gt; down but they have witnesses to claim to have heard them say this
&gt; (including police officers).
">

Even if they had agreed to keep their property separate, that wouldn't
change a thing.  Only if if your mother had actually waived any right
to share in the estate would anything change.

She's entitled to half the community property and (assuming two or more
children) one-third of the rest of the estate, including the house.
She doesn't have to take the house, only her share of its value.  But
she is entitled to her share of the whole thing.

