When it comes to wills and trusts, if it's not in writing -- and
properly witnessed -- it doesn't exist.

Your mom needs a lawyer.  Trying to do this herself in something as
complicated as probate is just asking for grief.  Your post implies
that there is a lot of money at stake here, so a few hundred $ to see
an attorney is money _very_ well spent.

Simplistic analysis:

California is a community property state.  That means that half of
anything the husband earned during the marriage is _automatically_
hers.  In addition, if he mingled his money with hers after the
marriage, there's a good chance that it is _all_ community property.

In addition, there's an assumption that you intend to provide for your
spouse.  If you make a will after marriage, you can exclude your
spouse (*except* for community property), but if you fail to amend
your will (or trust) when you get married, the law makes default
provisions.  From the California Probate Code, section 21610, that
would be *all* of the community property and quasi-community property
(not just half of it), *plus* half of her husbands's separate
property.

As for the debts, those are probably community too.  I think that means
they would be assessed against the community property first.  If there
isn't enough community and quasi-community proprty, she would have to
pay half and the other half would be assessed against his separate
property.  But if the debts are entirely in his name, there is a good
chance they would be subtracted from his separate property, *not* the
community property.  It is certainly *not* the case that she should
pay 100% of the debts, as the children are proposing.

I would say that Mom is in a fairly strong bargaining position -- if
she insists on everything the law allows she would get all the
community property plus half of the rest -- including the house.  I
will assume she just wants half of the estate _excluding_ the house,
and I think with the aid of a lawyer she should be able to negotiate
that result.  But she should *not* try to do this on her own.

Her best bet is to ask her personal attorney -- the one who handles
routine matters like wills -- to recommend a specialist in
probate law.  If she doesn't have a personal attorney, ask your friends,
relatives, and co-workers to ask their attorney for such a
recommendation.  If several come back with the same name, call that
one first.

If all else fails, ask your county Bar Association for their referral
list, or look in the yellow pages.  But a referral from somebody you
trust is better than relying on a YP ad, and the Bar Association just
lists every lawyer who _says_ he/she works in that speciality.

Call up and ask for an appointment.  Ask how much he will charge
for the initial consulation.  When she has described the situation to
him, she can ask how much he will charge to handle the case.
