I'm not a CA lawyer, so just a couple of quick thoughts.  First, you say
there is a probate case, but talk about  a trust.  "Probate" is the
court process to distribute property according to a "will, not a
"trust."  It is an important distinction because the rules are likely
very different.

For example, in Oregon, there is a statute that says that a Will is
revoked by a subsequent marriage.  Not so with a trust.  If there is a
similar CA statute, then you really want to know . . . Right?

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; So do his children have a leg to stand on?
">

I hope you are asking because your mom has a lawyer and you are trying
to find out some info for your self.  If not, if mom does not have a
lawyer, then it does not matter whether the kids are right, she will lose.

Part of the reason is that both probate and trust laws are set up in a
way that makes it relatively easy to resolve many cases where there are
ambiguous facts.  The system acts as a "filter".  The estate's lawyer
reaches an opinion as to the way it should come out.  They tell all the
affected people, and if there is no objection in proper form, then
that's the way it is.  My guess (and it's only a guess) is that you are
asking now, because you have such a notice and the clock is ticking on a
response.

If I am right, and there is serious money at stake, then step away from
the computer and take Mom to a real live lawyer . . . NOW!

